&gt;&gt;&gt;And, by one assertion, I hope you don&#39;t mean a maximum of one 
&gt;&gt;&gt;physical &quot;assertEquals&quot;!?
&gt;&gt;&gt;      
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;I think that&#39;s exactly what he means.  When I first started writing
&gt;&gt;Junit tests I had many assertions in my test methods.  Lately, as I
&gt;&gt;learn more about TDD, I&#39;ve been trying to limit my unit tests to only
&gt;&gt;one assertion per test method.  I find that by having only one 
&gt;&gt;assertion
&gt;&gt;per test method it keeps my tests much more focused and easier to
&gt;&gt;understand.  Once I get more than 2 or 3 assertions in a test method I
&gt;&gt;start to look at how I can split that one test up into 2 or more tests.
&gt;&gt;Give it a try, you might find that you like it.
&gt;&gt;
